A Discussion is currently on-going about when and how the group of Lots may be used.
In principle we see that the group of lots is needed for the EO at tendering time. Before that, the elements that relate to more than one lot, establish their relations trhough the property "applies to multiple" lots meaning that the set of lots that are the "range" of that domain element share the same property.
Lots are specified in the Procurement Procedure Technical Specifications.
Beware that the Tender Validity Date (deadline) applies to the Tender but may be predefined by the Procuring Entity.
There can not be a disjoint between the two classes
This needs to be reviewed taking into account that the ESPD Response already contains this information.
Double-click on this link to see the rest of classes associated to Procurement Procedure.
A specific business rule would be needed to control possible inconsistency generated by the concurrence of DocumentRestricted and definesAccessTo properties.
The Planned Procurement Part Legal Basis should match the Procedure Legal Basis once this is launched.

We have to work on the naming of the code identifiers, as these code may be taken as representatives of the documents in themselves whilst they are intended to specify to what type of submitable document the deadlines are referred to.
(TO BE FURTHER DISCUSSED)
The sum of individual lots may not necessarily be equal to the value of its group of lots.
The cardinality is 0..1 (optional) because the Directives (e.g. Directive 2014/24/EU Annex V) does not oblige to have this data.
The property linking Tender and Tenderer (submits/is submitted by) shall not be used to get to the Winner from the Contract. Instead "refers to signatory party Winner" MUST be used.
Participant Name and Participation Payment is expected only when the Design Contest Type is "RESTRICTED".

Beware that the indivIuals of Framework Agreements that are Techniques are different from the individuals of Framework Agreements that are contracts. They are used for different purposes and in different moments.
The lifecycle of Techniques are different from the legal life-cycle of Contracts. These two periods are used in different moments and different purposes, but they're dependent and rules need to be drafted to control that they are not inconsistent.
Examples:
In other words,
the property "has Validity Period" is "reserved to" Technicques, to explain the valid duration of the technique, whilst the "has Duration" property domain is "Contract".
We may need a class Variant that identifies the variant.
Participant Name and Participation Payment is expected only when the Design Contest Type is "RESTRICTED".
DO NOT FORGET LINKING THE PIN CFC AND THE DPS. See also Issues #212 and #213.

We have deleted the Reserved Contract Type (Code) property from the Post Award Terms. Instead we have defined a new class named "Participation Criterion" (see diagram "Procurement Criterion" for details).
WG decision 2019-01-16

To verify if the accessibility criteria should be here or whether it should be in Procurement, Award, Selection or Participation Criterion.
Keeping the accessibility criteria herein we put an extra burden on the developers as they probably would expect them linked to the "Strategic Procurement" class instead, which is the place where the eForms puts it.

PLEASE DO NOT FORGET THAT THE EVALUATION IS NOT ONLY ABOUT TENDERS, BUT REQUESTS FOR PARTICIPATION CAN ALSO BE ASSESSED BY THE CA.
We will have to model this when analysing the eEvaluation. Please see:
- Issue #213 about DPS, and - Directive 24, Article 34, namely paragraphs 2 and 5

When analysing the Awarding phase we need to heed attention to the fact that DPS has specific requirements that are dictated by the Contract (and that may not have been notified in the Contract Notice). These requirements would affect the delivery terms, for example.
TO BE DISCUSSED AND RE-ANALYSED. This is also being analysed by NO's Lawyers.

From Directive 24:
Contracting authorities should conduct such a comparative assessment by first determining which tenders best fulfil the award criteria laid down for each individual lot and then comparing it with the tenders submitted by a particular tenderer for a specific combination of lots

Recital (79) mentions explicitely that the evaluation is done per lot. The concept of "group" cannot actually be linked to the Tender as it refers to the combination of lots at evaluation time for award criteria used for comparative assessment between the tenders with combined lots and tenders with individual lots.
eFroms calls this class "Tender".

properties.documentation:
A role of an agent that awards the contract.
Additional information: Examples of a buyer can be the role of contracting authority, contracting entity, a defence contractor, an international organisation, or an organisation awarding a contract subsidized by a contracting authority.
WG Approval 28/04/2020

documentation.value:
Role of entities, which:
(a) are contracting authorities or public undertakings and which pursue one of the activities referred to in Articles 8 to 14 of the Directive 2014/25/EU.
(b) when they are not contracting authorities or public undertakings, have as one of their activities any of the activities referred to in Articles 8 to 14, or any combination thereof and operate on the basis of special or exclusive rights granted by a competent authority of a Member State.
Additional Information
The indicator is needed in order to discriminate between those contracts where the Contracting Entity acts as a Contracting Authority undergoing the limits and the rules of Directive 24 and those where it acts as a Contracting Entity, with certain relaxed constraints. For example, the Contracting Entities have different thresholds for the application of Directive 24 if compared with Contracting Authorities.
WG Approval 28/04/2020

The principal sectoral area in which an organisation operates.
Additional information
The activities associated with buyers are derived from the top level of the Classification of the functions of the government (COFOG) from the United Nations Statistics Division.
The activities associated with buyer are derived from sectors explicitly falling within the sectoral directive (2014/25/EU Art. 8 - Art. 14).
WG Approval 05/05/2020

In the ePO ontology a taxonomy with all activities, based on different classifications (COFOG, UTILITIES, NACE), will be provided. In ePO this field is to be used exclusively to complement the definition attached to the MainActivityCode.
However, in eForms there is the code "other" to cover undefined activities. For mapping to this eForms feature one could also use this property.

properties.documentation:

Contracting authority procuring activities conducted on a permanent basis, in one of the following forms:[...](b) the award of public contracts or the conclusion of framework agreements for works, supplies or services intended for contracting authorities;

Software solutions and electronic devices for communication and exchange of information between buyers and economic operators.
Additional Information
Lots may use ad-hoc electronic means of communication that are not generally available such as specific solutions for secure and dedicated communication or non-standard eCatalogues.
See also Directive recitals 53 to 56.

properties.documentation:
A financial resource used to support the procurement.
Additional Information:
In the context of EU, funds can be divided into programmes, actions and projects.
Examples of EU funds are: the European Structural and Investment Funds, European Social Fund (ESF), the Connecting Europe Facility (CEF) programme, or the ISA2 programme and its actions (e.g. Action 2016.05 European Public Procurement Initiative, which supports the eProcurement Ontology under sub-action 3).
Funds may change between the lot and the contract, for example in the case of an emergency crisis, a contract may be financed by a budget that was not foreseen in the call.
